Analysis

The analysis below illustrate a detailed linear regression analysis aimed at predicting house SalePrice. The model incorporates multiple predictors, including categorical transformations and interaction terms, to capture complex relationships within the data.

The dataset, housedata was processed to include features thought to influence the sale price, like total square footage, neighborhood categories, and the year of remodeling. Features were engineered, such as combining basement and living area into total_sf, and transforming variables like neighborhood and year_remod_add into categorical bins.

The model used selected features that included both quantitative and qualitative attributes. Factors like garage_cars, bsmt_qual, and kitchen_qual were converted to factor variables, indicating an assumption that different levels within these variables differently affect the sale price. Interaction terms like weighted_sf_quality:neighborhood_price_category were included to examine if the impact of square footage quality varies by different neighborhood pricing tiers.

# Define selected features with updated names
selected_features <- c("sale_price", "overall_rating", "weighted_total_sf",
                       "total_sf", "neighborhood", "lot_area", "year_remod_add",
                       "garage_cars", "bsmt_qual", "kitchen_qual", "fireplaces")
#"sale_condition"

# Data preprocessing
housedata1 <- housedata %>%
  select(-id, -alley, -pool_qc, -fence, -misc_feature) %>%  # Drop unnecessary columns
  mutate(
    total_sf = total_bsmt_sf + gr_liv_area,# Create new TotalSF column
    overall_rating = (overall_cond + overall_qual)/2,
    weighted_total_sf = total_sf * (overall_rating/10),
    neighborhood = as.factor(neighborhood),
    bsmt_full_bath = as.factor(bsmt_full_bath),
    ms_zoning = as.factor(ms_zoning),
    house_style = as.factor(house_style),
    fireplaces = as.factor(fireplaces),
    garage_cars = as.factor(garage_cars)
  ) %>%
  drop_na(all_of(selected_features)) %>%  # Remove rows with NA in selected columns
  mutate(
  neighborhood_price_category = case_when(
    neighborhood %in% c("NoRidge", "NridgHt", "StoneBr", "Timber", "Veenker") ~ "High",   # High-end neighborhoods
    neighborhood %in% c("Crawfor", "ClearCr", "Somerst", "CollgCr", "Gilbert") ~ "Upper-Mid",  # Slightly lower than high
    neighborhood %in% c("NWAmes", "SawyerW", "Blmngtn", "Mitchel", "SWISU") ~ "Mid",  # Mid-tier
    neighborhood %in% c("Edwards", "BrkSide", "NAmes", "Sawyer", "NPkVill") ~ "Lower-Mid",  # Slightly lower than mid
    neighborhood %in% c("Blueste", "OldTown", "BrDale", "IDOTRR", "MeadowV") ~ "Low",  # Lowest-priced neighborhoods
    TRUE ~ "Mid"  # Default category
  )) %>%
  mutate(neighborhood_price_category = as.factor(neighborhood_price_category)) %>% 
  mutate(year_rmod_group = case_when(
    year_remod_add < 1980 ~ "Pre 1980",
    year_remod_add >= 1980 & year_remod_add < 2000 ~"1980-1999",
    year_remod_add > 1999 ~ "2000-2010"
  )) %>% 
  mutate(year_rmod_group = as.factor(year_rmod_group))

housedata2 = housedata1 %>% 
  filter(lot_area < 100000 & weighted_total_sf < 5200) %>% 
  select(-total_bsmt_sf, -gr_liv_area, -overall_cond, -overall_qual, -sale_price, sale_price)

# Define the linear regression formula
formula <- sale_price ~ weighted_total_sf : neighborhood_price_category + lot_area + year_rmod_group : bsmt_unf_sf + garage_cars + bsmt_qual + kitchen_qual

# Train the linear regression model
model <- lm(formula, data = housedata2)

#pairs(housep, panel=panel.smooth)

# Check for multicollinearity using VIF
#vif(model)

The Linear Model & More Visuals

A linear regression model was constructed using these features, with the formula incorporating both main effects and interactions to capture more nuanced effects.

Main Effects: Each significant coefficient (e.g., garage_cars, bsmt_qual) indicates how much the SalePrice is expected to change with one unit change in the predictor or moving from one category to another within the factor variables, holding all other variables constant. Interaction Effects: The highly significant interaction terms suggest that the effect of weighted_sf_quality on SalePrice differs significantly across different neighborhood price categories. For example, the positive and highly significant coefficient for weighted_sf_quality:neighborhood_price_categoryHigh indicates a much greater impact on sale prices in high-priced neighborhoods compared to the baseline category.

# You can now use `mytest` to validate the model.
predictions <- predict(model1, newdata = mytest)
#predictions

#Checking the performance
rmse <- sqrt(mean((mytest$sale_price - predictions)^2))
#print(rmse)

mae <- mean(abs(mytest$sale_price - predictions))
#print(mae)

# First, calculate Total Sum of Squares (TSS) and Residual Sum of Squares (RSS)
tss <- sum((mytest$sale_price - mean(mytest$sale_price))^2)
rss <- sum((mytest$sale_price - predictions)^2)

r_squared <- 1 - (rss / tss)
#print(r_squared)

n <- nrow(mytest)  # number of observations
p <- length(coef(model1)) - 1  # number of predictors, subtract 1 for the intercept

adjusted_r_squared <- 1 - ((1 - r_squared) * (n - 1) / (n - p - 1))
#print(adjusted_r_squared)

mse <- mean((mytest$sale_price - predictions)^2)
#print(mse)

The models performance was validated using a separate test dataset (mytest), which was not used in the model training. Performance metrics included:

RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error): Provides a measure of the average magnitude of the models prediction errors. MAE (Mean Absolute Error): Averages the absolute differences between predicted and actual values, giving a straightforward interpretation of error magnitude. R-squared: Indicates how well the data fit the regression model (the proportion of variance explained by the model). Adjusted R-squared: Adjusted for the number of predictors in the model, providing a more accurate measure when comparing models with different numbers of predictors.

Graphs: Scatter plots were generated to visually assess the distribution of SalePrice across different features in the model providing more insights into the datas structure.

This detailed approach not only fits a model to predict SalePrice effectively but also carefully examines and validates the relationships within the data, ensuring robust predictions. The use of both graphical and numerical summaries aids in understanding and communicating the models effectiveness and the underlying data characteristics.
